# business-documents / Typst invoice-maker

Render a beautiful, reproducible PDF invoice from a declarative data record using the official Typst Universe `invoice-maker` template (Adrian Sieber, ISC). Text-in / PDF-out: edit the data, recompile, get a byte-stable invoice. Supports taxes, discounts, cancellations, EN/DE, and custom banners/colors/fonts.

controls do
  business-documents.title: { label: "Invoice title", type: "text" }
  business-documents.invoice_id: { label: "Invoice ID", type: "text" }
  business-documents.biller: { label: "Biller name", type: "text" }
  business-documents.recipient: { label: "Recipient name", type: "text" }
  business-documents.item_description: { label: "Line item", type: "text" }
  business-documents.hourly_rate: { label: "Hourly rate", type: "range" }
  business-documents.source: { label: "invoice.typ", type: "textarea", file: "src/invoice.typ" }
end

## Required reading
- invoice-maker package (the template, ISC): https://typst.app/universe/package/invoice-maker/
- Typst official docs (language + reference): https://typst.app/docs/
- Typst LLM/agent skill file thread: https://forum.typst.app/t/llm-skill-file-for-claude-code-codex-etc/8397
- typst-claude-skill (ChanMeng666, community): https://github.com/ChanMeng666/typst-claude-skill
- claude-skill-typst (lucifer1004, community): https://github.com/lucifer1004/claude-skill-typst

## Render
```bash
# install (native binary, Apache-2.0)
brew install typst   # or: cargo install --locked typst-cli

# compile (first run fetches @preview/invoice-maker from the registry)
typst compile src/invoice.typ out/invoice.pdf
```

## Failure modes
- Field name/shape mismatch: keys must match the package record (biller, recipient, items, rates, taxes). Adjust per the Universe README if compile errors.
- Version drift: README example pins `invoice-maker:1.0.0`; current is `1.1.0`. Pin `1.1.0` for reproducibility.
- Airgap: first compile needs network to fetch the `@preview` package. Pre-warm `~/.cache/typst` or vendor the package for offline CI.
- Missing fonts: custom fonts must be on the system or passed via `--font-path`; otherwise Typst falls back silently.
